The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Saturday, June 19, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Mayor Subrata Mukherjee has written to eminent Calcuttans, including former mayors, asking them to help him out with the 2004-2005 municipal budget. According to CMC officials, in his letter, Mukherjee has provided details of the previous years budget and the total amount collected in revenues by the civic body. The mayor will hold a meeting on this matter before presenting the budget.																																																		The Calcutta Municipal Corporation on Friday started a drive to remove khatals from Gobindapur, near Jodhpur Park. Mayor-in-council member Rajib Deb and local councillor Ratan Dey were present during the operation. They said the khatals had been set up illegally and were responsible for choking the drainage system of the area. The clogged drains had led to waterlogging during the recent showers.																																																		Commuters on the Howrah-Burdwan cord line held a sit-in on the railway tracks for two hours on Friday morning at Sealdah to protest the decision for letting Rajdhani Express pass before the local train they were travelling in. Eight local trains were cancelled.																																																		Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee has asked library workers to be more active and adopt all possible measures to reach people. According to Bhattacharjee, who was speaking at the inauguration of the two-day state committee conference of Paschimbanga Sadharaner Granthagar Karmi Samity, in Sarat Sadan, Howrah, the budget for library development in the present fiscal year has been fixed at Rs 58 crore so that the 3,481 state-run libraries could be modernised. Library minister Nemai Mal and MP Swadesh Chakraborty were present.																																																		An Indo-British consortium has submitted a scoping report on a light rail transit (LRT) network in Calcutta to state transport minister Subhas Chakraborty on Friday. Representatives of KLRS, a group of four UK-based companies and an Indian firm, met Chakraborty and his colleagues in the transport department and made a presentation on the technical modalities of a mass rapid transit system based on the light rail network. The consortium had earlier placed a preliminary proposal before the government on the model.																																																		Peak-hour railway traffic was disrupted for more than four hours on Friday at Howrah as Trinamul Congress workers demostrated on the tracks of the Bandel-Katwa section, demanding the functioning of the new Kalinagar station near Nabadweep.TO Southern Initiatives for staging a play called Heerur Swapno based on environmental issues relevant to slum dwellers at Deshbandhu Park
